computers, smart phones, and other visual media devices.
HB78 INTRODUCED
113 §26-24-41
114 (a)(1) The Research and Evaluation Team within the
115 department shall develop guidelines for determining what
116 constitutes "high-quality programming." The guidelines shall
117 be based on current evidence-based research and practices
118 related to screen time use. The department may consult with
119 the Department of Human Resources and the State Board of
120 Education in developing the guidelines.
121 (2) In setting the guidelines, the department shall
122 consider, but not be limited to, the following factors:
123 a. The target audience of the program, and whether it
124 is age-appropriate in an early childhood education setting.
125 b. The pacing of the program, with a preference toward
126 slow-paced programming.
127 c. Whether the programming is free of violence.
128 d. Whether the programming is free of advertisement
129 that the department determines is harmful to children.
130 (b) Each early childhood education program shall
131 implement screen time standards as follows:
132 (1) For children under two years of age, screen time is
133 prohibited. For purposes of this subdivision, the term "screen
134 time" does not include live, interactive video communication,
135 such as a video call with a child's family.
136 (2) For children two through four years of age:
137 a. Screen time may not exceed more than 30 minutes per
138 day, nor 90 minutes per week, with preference given to
139 interactive group viewing that promotes discussion and social
140 interaction; and
Page 5

interaction; and
HB78 INTRODUCED
141 b. Individual screen time is prohibited.
142 (3) For all childhood education programs:
143 a. All screen time must meet the department's standard
144 for high-quality programming and be actively supervised by
145 staff; and
146 b. Background television and passive screen time is
147 prohibited.
148 §26-24-42
149 (a) The Research and Evaluation Team within the
150 department shall develop research-based guidelines on healthy
151 screen time practices for children from birth through five
152 years of age. The guidelines shall be based on current
153 evidence-based research and practices related to screen time
154 use. The department may consult with the Department of Human
155 Resources and the State Board of Education in developing the
156 guidelines.
157 (b) The guidelines shall emphasize:
158 (1) The importance of play, reading, physical activity,
159 and caregiver-child interaction.
160 (2) The risks of excessive screen use on children,
161 including developmental delays and behavioral impacts.
162 (3) Strategies for setting screen-free routines in the
163 home.
164 (c) The department shall make the guidelines publicly
165 available at no cost to parents and guardians in the state.
166 §26-24-43
167 (a) The department, in collaboration with the
168 Department of Human Resources and the State Board of
